SIMPLE: retention
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Retention
<hw>Re*ten"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>retentio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>r⟦eacute⟧tention</ets>. See
<er>Retain</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of retaining, or the
state of being ratined.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The power of retaining; retentiveness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No woman's heart⟦br⟧
So big, to hold so much; they lack <qex>retention</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which contains something, as a tablet; a
<?/<?/<?/<?/ of preserving impressions.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The act of withholding; retraint; reserve.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Place of custody or confinement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The right of withholding a debt, or
of retaining property until a debt due to the person claiming the right
be duly paid; a lien.</def> <rj><au>Erskine. Craig.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Retention cyst</b></col> <fld>(Med.)</fld>, <cd>a cyst
produced by obstruction of a duct leading from a secreting organ and the
consequent retention of the natural secretions.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retentive</ent>⟦br⟧
